I tend to agree with you Cook.  Iwent from a participant in the anti-war movement to active duty Marine in Vietnam within six months.  The political dogma of an idealist movement(anti-war) was very disillusioning.  I had my head cracked by poplice batons and was arrested several times all in pursuit of peace.  What a joke.  Peace was the furthest thing from anyone's mind.  It was get high and get laid.  My   induction into the USMC was the best thing that could have happened to me.  I met the most sincere and caring people I've ever met.  The camaradaire (today called &quot;male bonding&quot; if you want to be politically correct.  I came from a middle class family and could have gone to college to get out of service.  I felt that it was hypocritical (sp?) to be protesting something I only had biased information on both left and right wing.  I like Cook am proud of what I did.  I am never ashamed to state that I am a Vietnam Combat Vetertan.  I respect the right of others to have their views about the war, however when they disrespect me and/or my views (which they did and still do today) I take offense.  Jed, my friend I respect how hard you worked to avoid the draft, think what you could have done with all that energy had it been channelled in a different direction.  Like you, I cannot change the past, only learn from it.  I agree that the war in Vietnam didn't require our participation, however it's easier to sit here 30 years later and say that.  I don't need your 'I told you so's.'Let's heal as a nation.
